\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Introduction"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Continuous optimization constitutes one of the most extensively studied areas in computational mathematics and computer science,
 encompassing problems in which a real-valued objective function must be minimised or maximised over a continuous search space,
 typically subject to bound or equality constraints.
 The practical difficulty of such problems arises from properties such as multimodality,
 non-convexity,
 high dimensionality,
 and the absence of analytical gradient information,
 which render exact methods computationally intractable in many real-world scenarios 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Floudas"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Over the past three decades,
 metaheuristic algorithms have emerged as a widely adopted class of approximate solvers capable of exploring large,
 complex search spaces without relying on derivative information.
 Seminal contributions in this class include the Genetic Algorithm (GA) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Holland"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 Particle Swarm optimization (PSO) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Kennedy"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 and Differential Evolution (DE) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Storn"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 alongside a steadily expanding body of variants and hybrid approaches,
 each proposing improvements in convergence speed,
 solution quality,
 or robustness.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The proliferation of metaheuristic methods has,
 however,
 introduced a parallel challenge:
 the rigorous,
 fair,
 and reproducible evaluation of algorithmic performance.
 Benchmarking an optimization algorithm is a non-trivial undertaking that requires careful attention to experimental design,
 the selection of representative test problems,
 the choice of performance metrics,
 the number of independent runs,
 and the application of appropriate statistical tests 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Beiranvand"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 In practice,
 inconsistent benchmarking protocols lead to results that are difficult to reproduce,
 compare,
 or generalise across studies 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Bartz-Beielstein"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Sensitivity of algorithm performance to hyper-parameter settings,
 and the dependence of relative algorithm rankings on problem instance characteristics,
 further complicate the interpretation of benchmarking outcomes 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Kononova"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 These concerns have motivated calls within the optimization community for standardised,
 transparent,
 and tool-supported benchmarking workflows.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Several software frameworks have been developed to address aspects of this challenge.
 COCO 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Hansen"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 provides a black-box benchmarking environment with automated post-processing,
 IOHprofiler 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Doerr"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 offers a web-based interface for profiling iterative heuristics,
 Nevergrad 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Rapin"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 pymoo 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Blank"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 MEALPY 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Van"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 NiaPy 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Vrbančič"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 opfunu 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Van2"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 OPTIMUS 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Tsoulos"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 and GLOBe 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Serré"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 each contribute algorithmic libraries and varying degrees of experimental support.
 Nevertheless,
 as detailed in Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:RelatedWork"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 none of these tools combines a native desktop Graphical User Interface (GUI) with command-line operation,
 built-in method and problem sensitivity analysis,
 algorithmic complexity analysis across both methods and problem dimensions,
 embedded non-parametric statistical testing,
 and in-GUI extensibility for new methods and problems all within a single,
 cross-platform,
 self-contained framework.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This paper presents OptimSolution,
 an open-source framework for the systematic benchmarking and multi-faceted analysis of continuous optimization methods.
 An earlier,
 undocumented prototype is publicly accessible at:
 
\begin_inset Flex URL
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
https://github.com/charilog/optimsolution
\end_layout

\end_inset

,
 the present work constitutes its first formal description and introduces a substantially extended feature set.
 The framework is operable via both a Qt-based GUI and a CLI,
 and runs natively on Linux,
 Windows,
 and macOS.
 It supports four execution modes Single (includes Complexity Analysis),
 Batch,
 Method Sensitivity Analysis,
 and Problem Sensitivity Analysis.
 Statistical validation via Wilcoxon signed-rank 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Wilcoxon"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and Friedman tests 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Friedman"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 is integrated natively,
 and all results are exportable as structured CSV files or publication-ready PNG figures.
 A key design objective is extensibility:
 new optimization methods and benchmark problems can be registered through the GUI without modifying the core codebase.
\end_layout

