\begin_layout Subsection
GUI Execution Performance
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:GUIPerformance"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Although the GUI and the CLI share an identical computational core,
 the GUI achieves substantially lower wall-clock execution times on multi-run experiments when the CLI is used in its default mode with output directed to the terminal.
 To quantify this effect systematically,
 jSO was applied to the six-element circular antenna array synthesis problem 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Das"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 (D = 12) for 30 independent runs under identical configuration across three conditions:
 GUI,
 CLI with terminal output,
 and CLI with all output suppressed via PowerShell redirection (| Out-Null).
 As reported in the CLI summary (Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:cli"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

),
 the mean time per run was 8.38 seconds,
 yielding a total wall-clock time of 251.37 seconds,
 with a best objective value of 0.00680964 and a 100% success rate across all 30 runs.
 The GUI completed the same experiment in 125 seconds (Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:gui"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

),
 delivering an identical best objective value and convergence profile a speedup factor of approximately 
\begin_inset Formula $2.0×$
\end_inset

 over the default CLI.
 When CLI output was fully suppressed,
 the wall-clock time dropped to 125.23 seconds,
 statistically identical to the GUI.
 This result demonstrates that the 
\begin_inset Formula $2.0×$
\end_inset

 speedup is attributable entirely to terminal I/O overhead in the default CLI mode:
 the GUI accumulates process output in an internal buffer and flushes it at fixed intervals rather than rendering each line in real time,
 effectively eliminating the overhead that dominates CLI wall-clock time when output is directed to the terminal.
 The underlying computational workload is identical in both interfaces.
\end_layout

